The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Tuesday, May 31, 2005 

 BRIEFS

 Midnapore, May 30: Debasish Chakraborty, the life-term convict who escaped from Midnapore Central Jail and was arrested yesterday, said he had run away to meet his parents.

 Convicted for murdering his girlfriend and attempting to kill his mother, Debasish was produced before the Midnapore judicial magistrate, who remanded him to jail custody and took his confessional statement. My maternal uncles looked after me in my childhood. That is why I went there first, Debasish said. 

 Calcutta: A fire broke out in a godown packed with electronic goods in Beliaghatas Radhamadbah Dutta Garden Lane on Monday. Residents saw smoke coming out of the godowns ventilator around 10.30 pm and informed the fire department. No casualty or injury was reported.

 Calcutta: The director of agriculture, D. Konar, has said the state is not facing a drought-like situation, despite parts of Bankura, West Midnapore, Purulia and Burdwan reeling under intense heat. 

 Calcutta: The results of the 10th State-Level Eligibility Test will be published on Tuesday, said Ajit Banik, the chairman of the West Bengal College Service Commission. The test is conducted every year to recruit teachers for universities and colleges.

 Hooghly: Police fished out the body of a boy from a ferry ghat near Serampore on Monday. He was identified as Nabarun Bhadhuri, a Class XI student of a Barrackpore school.

 Chinsurah: Trouble erupted among CPM rivals at Haripal in Hooghly district on Monday after CPM panchayat member Zahed Alis house was set on fire. In retaliation, Ali led his associates to raid the house of another CPM leader, Abu Sufian Mullick. He was dragged out of his house and assaulted. 

 Calcutta: Dacoits raided two schools in Patharpratima in South 24- Parganas on Monday. Police said the gangs broke open cash boxes containing teachers salaries. 




